  "text": "Once upon a matchday — it was the round of 16, on the 4th of July 2026 — two teams walked out under the soft evening lights. Morocco marched into the last eight and ended the co-hosts' dream on home soil. For Canada, one of three host nations, this was the end of a home World Cup; for Morocco, a fourth straight knockout scalp and a statement of intent.\n\nIn the 50th minute, Azzedine Ounahi sent the ball gently home, and the score whispered 0–1. In the 82nd minute, Azzedine Ounahi sent the ball gently home, and the score whispered 0–2. In the 98th minute, Soufiane Rahimi sent the ball gently home, and the score whispered 0–3.\n\nAzzedine Ounahi took over after the interval, first curling home a right-footed shot through traffic after a clever Achraf Hakimi free-kick, then punishing a stretched Canadian back line for his second. Substitute Soufiane Rahimi, released by Brahim Díaz, made the win emphatic deep into stoppage time. Canada huffed and puffed in front of their own crowd but never truly troubled the Moroccan defence. Morocco, the surprise semi-finalists of 2022, again looked like the tournament's great disruptors.\n\nAnd so the story ended Canada 0–3 Morocco. Morocco carried on their long journey, and Canada lay down to rest. Every goal in this tale is a true one — kept safe and provable on the blockchain by TxLINE — so you can close your eyes knowing not a single fact was ever made up. Sleep well, and goodnight.",
